Advise the Accountable Manager on accepting training staff.

6.1.5 Equipment for Operations under IFR

In accordance with NCO.IDE.A.125, airplanes operated under IFR shall be equipped with a means of measuring and displaying the following:

Magnetic heading;
Time in hours, minutes and seconds;
Pressure altitude;
Indicated airspeed;
Vertical speed;
Turn and slip;
Attitude;
Stabilized heading;
Outside air temperature;
A means of indicating when the supply of power to the gyroscopic instruments is not adequate; and
A means of preventing malfunction of the airspeed indicating system due to condensation or icing.

Note:
A means of measuring and displaying the time in hours, minutes and seconds may be a wrist watch capable of the same functions.

Note:
Individual equipment requirements may be met by combinations of instruments, by integrated flight systems or by a combination of parameters on electronic displays. The information so available to each required pilot should not be less than that required in the applicable operational requirements, and the equivalent safety of the installation should be approved during type certification of the airplane for the intended type of operation.

Note:
The means of measuring and indicating turn and slip, airplane attitude and stabilized airplane heading may be met by combinations of instruments or by integrated flight director systems, provided that the safeguards against total failure, inherent in the three separate instruments, are retained.

6.1 Airplanes

In accordance with NCO.IDE.A.100, the following instruments and equipment, when required for the intended flight operations, shall be approved in accordance with the applicable airworthiness requirements if they are:

Used by the flight crew to control the flight path;
Used to comply with NCO.IDE.A.190 (radio communication equipment requirements);
Used to comply with NCO.IDE.A.195 (navigation equipment requirements);
Installed in the airplane.

The following items, when required for the intended flight operations, do not need equipment approval:

Spare fuses;
Independent portable lights;
An accurate timepiece;
First-aid kit;
Survival and signaling equipment;
Sea anchor and equipment for mooring;
Child restraint device.

Instruments and equipment not required for the intended flight operations, as well as any other equipment not required by other applicable Annexes but carried on a flight, shall comply with the following:

The information provided shall not be used by the flight crew to comply with operational communication or navigation requirements;
The equipment shall not affect the airworthiness of the airplane, even in case of failure or malfunction.

Instruments and equipment shall be readily operable or accessible from the flight crew station.

All required emergency equipment shall be easily accessible for immediate use.

4.1.4 VFR at night
In accordance with SERA.5005c, VFR flights at night may be authorized under the following conditions:
• If leaving the vicinity of an aerodrome, a flight plan shall be submitted;
• Flights shall establish and maintain two way radio communication on the appropriate ATS communication channel, when available;
• The VMC visibility and distance from cloud minima as specified in 4.1.1 above shall apply, except that:
✓ The ceiling shall not be less than 1.500ft;
✓ The reduced flight visibility provisions specified in remark (**) of 4.1.1 shall not apply;
✓ In airspace classes B, C, D, E, F and G at and below 3.000 ft AMSL or 1.000ft AGL, whichever is the higher, the pilot shall maintain continuous sight of the surface;
• Except when necessary for take-off or landing, or except when specifically authorized by the CAA, a VFR flight at night shall be flown at a level that is at least 1.000ft above the highest obstacle located within 8km of the estimated position of the aircraft.
Note 1: In Belgium, VFR flights at night are authorized, except for gliders, DPM, ULM and RPA.
Note 2: In Luxembourg, VFR flights at night may be operated in Luxembourg CTR, Luxembourg TMA (up to FL 95) or class G airspace (up to 2.000 ft AMSL) after approval of the CAA.

1.3 Chief Flight Instructor

Chief Flight Instructor
It is the responsibility of the Chief Flight Instructor to:
Organize Standardization Meetings with all Flight Instructors (at least once/year);
Ensure all Flight Instructors and Synthetic Training Instructors receive proper Initial Standardization Training;
Ensure all Flight Instructors and Synthetic Training Instructors receive proper Recurrent Standardization Training;
Ensure all Flight Instructors and Synthetic Training Instructors are evaluated yearly on their:
Teaching and Learning Skills;
Currency of License, Ratings and Medicals;
Application and knowledge of the Rules and Regulations;
Application and knowledge of the Standard Operating Procedures;
Advise the Head of Training on accepting training staff.

8.3.5.2 Preflight Check
Before each flight, the pilot-in-command should perform the following checks to ensure the continued safe operation of the EFB during the flight:

General check of the EFB operation by switching it ON and checking that the applications they intend to use in flight are adequately operative;
Check of the remaining available battery power, if applicable, to ensure the availability of the EFB during the planned flight;
Check of the version effectivity of the EFB databases, if applicable (e.g. for charts, performance calculation and weight and balance applications); and
Check that an appropriate backup is available when a chart application or an application displaying aircraft checklists is used.

1.4 Chief Theoretical Knowledge Instructor

Chief Theoretical Knowledge Instructor
It is the responsibility of the Chief Theoretical Knowledge Instructor to:
Organise Standardization Meetings with all Theoretical Knowledge Instructors (at least once/year);
Ensure all Theoretical Knowledge Instructors receive proper Initial Standardization Training;
ensure all Theoretical Knowledge Instructors receive proper Recurrent Standardization Training;
ensure all Theoretical Knowledge Instructors are evaluated yearly on their:
Teaching and Learning Skills;
Application of the Rules and Regulations;
Application of the Standard Operating Procedures;
Advise the Head of Training on accepting training staff.

1.5 Chief Operations Officer

Chief Operations Officer
It is the responsibility of the Chief Operations Officer to:
Upon request of the Accountable Manager, publish any vacant Nominated Person, training staff, Operations Officer or any other position within EuroPilot Center;
Invite and organize the intake conversation with candidate Nominated Persons, Operations Officer, training staff etc;
Advise the Accountable Manager on accepting a candidate;
Schedule, upon request of the Head of Training, Chief Flight Instructor or Chief Theoretical Knowledge Instructor, Initial or Recurrent Training for all training staff.

2. INITIAL TRAINING

6.1.2 Operating Lights

In accordance with NCO.IDE.A.115, airplanes operated at night shall be equipped with:

An anti-collision light system;
Navigation / position lights;
A landing light;
Lighting supplied from the airplane’s electrical system to provide adequate illumination for all instruments and equipment essential to the safe operation of the airplane;
Lighting supplied from the airplane’s electrical system to provide illumination in all passenger compartments;
An independent portable light for each crew member station.

3.1.1 Aim of the course
A refresher course will be organized each year during the months of January & February for every Flight- and Theoretical Knowledge Instructor individually; or at any time:
After the absence of an Instructor for 12 months or more;
A major update of any Training Manual;
A major update of Standard Operating Procedures;
Introduction of new/updated regulations;
Introduction of a new type of aircraft.

We refer to the Proficiency Forms on the E-Gle Online System.

7.2 Instructor Evaluation

The Head of Training is responsible for organizing a yearly individual Instructor evaluation. The evaluation shall be based on:
The Proficiency Check results;
Homestudy Progress Check results;
The Training Feedback Forms;
Occurence Reports.

A digital Instructor Evaluation Report will be produced and discussed during the individual Instructor Evaluation.

We refer to OM Annex 23: Instructor Evaluation Report.

